b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe1411.htm)  [Next](sbe1413.htm)\n\n* * *\n\n### CHAPTER IX.\n\n1\\. A hermit shall wear (his hair in) braids, and dress (in garments made of)\nbark and skins; 1\n\n2\\. And he shall not enter a village. 2\n\n3\\. He shall not step on ploughed (land). 3\n\n4\\. He shall gather wild growing roots and fruit (only). 4\n\n5\\. He shall remain chaste. 5\n\n6\\. His heart shall be full of meekness. 6\n\n7\\. He shall honour guests coming to his hermitage with alms (consisting of)\nroots and fruit. 7\n\n8\\. He shall only give, not receive (presents).\n\n9\\. He shall bathe at morn, noon, and eve. 9\n\n10\\. Kindling a fire according to the (rule of the) _S_ rama _n_ aka (Sutra),\nhe shall offer the Agnihotra. 10\n\n11\\. After (living in this manner during) six months, 11\n\np. 46\n\nhe shall dwell at the root of a tree, keeping no fire and having no house.\n\n12\\. He (who in this manner) gives (their due) to gods, manes, and men, will\nattain endless (bliss in) heaven.\n\n* * *\n\n### Footnotes\n\n[45:1](sbe1412.htm#fr_255) **IX**. Vish _n_ u XCIV, 8-9; Gautama III, 34. K\n_ri_ sh _n_ apa _n_ _d_ ita takes _k_ ira, 'bark,' to mean '(made of) grass,'\ne.g. of Mu _\xc3\xb1_ _g_ a or Balva _g_ a.\n\n[45:2](sbe1412.htm#fr_256) Gautama III, 33. The particle 'and' probably\nindicates that the hermit is not to enter any other inhabited place.\n\n[45:3](sbe1412.htm#fr_257) Gautama III, 32.\n\n[45:4](sbe1412.htm#fr_258) Vish _n_ u XCV, 5.\n\n[45:5](sbe1412.htm#fr_259) Vish _n_ u XCV, 7.\n\n[45:6](sbe1412.htm#fr_260) Manu VI, 8.\n\n[45:7](sbe1412.htm#fr_261) Gautama III, 30.\n\n[45:9](sbe1412.htm#fr_262) Vish _n_ u XCV, 10.\n\n[45:10](sbe1412.htm#fr_263) Gautama III, 27. K _ri_ sh _n_ apa _n_ _d_ ita and\nMSS. B. F. read _s_ rava _n_ akena, and the rest avar _n_ akena. I read _s_\nrama _n_ akena, 'according to the rule of the _S_ rama _n_ aka Sutra,' in\naccordance with Gautama's text. Baudhayana, too, uses the same word.\n\n[45:11](sbe1412.htm#fr_264) Manu VI, 25.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: Chapter X](sbe1413.htm)\n\n"